player.seasonOutlook: Haliburton was in the midst of a giant leap in his fourth season when injury struck. Through his first 30 games, Haliburton was averaging 24.9 PPG (50.1 FG%, 86.3 FT%, 40.8 3P%), 12.7 APG, 4.1 RPG, 3.6 3PG, 1.0 SPG and 0.7 BPG with only 2.5 TO. Those numbers had him firmly in the top-5 of fantasy hoops rankings with a chance to challenge for the top spot. Unfortunately, he injured his hamstring in January and had to miss a lot of time, and even when he returned he was clearly not the same physically. If Haliburton returns to health and form, he could challenge Shai Gilgeous-Alexander for the most productive guard in fantasy basketball.

Barnes took a major step forward in his third season, establishing himself as the new franchise player on the Raptors as they decided to move on from both Pascal Siakam and OG Anunoby. Barnes exploded past his previous career marks in every category, with a 20/8/6 statline with still quite a bit of upside to grow. The 23-year old also contributed in the sparser categories, averaging 1.7 3PG, 1.5 BPG and 1.3 SPG to give himself even more value in category leagues (borderline first/second-round) than points (second round).

Though the impression was that Harden was in Joel Embiid's shadow in Philadelphia and that he returned to his usual levels once he "escaped" to the Clippers, the truth is that Harden's numbers went down across the board once he arrived in Los Angeles. He took his fewest shots since he became a starter more than a decade ago, and scored his fewest points since winning Sixth Man of the Year in 2011-12. His assists, rebounds, 3-pointers and steals also dropped year-over-year. While part of this may be due to age, with Harden entering his age 35 season, he was also on a loaded Clippers team featuring several other star talents. With Paul George and Russell Westbrook out of town, Harden may have to carry a larger role with closer to his typical usage this season. Harden's volume 3-point shooting, solid steals and even a near-block per game make him a better prospect in category leagues, top-20, than his top-30 valuation in points leagues.

Turner has settled into his role as a shooter-scorer-shotblocker at center for the Pacers. Playing off Tyrese Haliburton and the shots he can create, Turner averages in the upper-teens of points with about 1.5 treys per night. He also blocks two shots per game, though his value really peaks in the years that number is closer to three. He isn't a big rebounder for a center, but in the new Pacers frontcourt he cedes some of the boards to Pascal Siakam but assumes a heavier rim protection role. Turner is a top-60 prospect in points leagues, but his shot-blocking makes him top-40 in category leagues.

Mobley finished third in the Defensive Player of the Year vote as a sophomore, then made incremental improvements in year 3. Most of those improvements centered around scoring efficiency, where he set new career-marks of 58.0 FG%, 71.9 FT% and 37.3 3P%. Mobley and Jarrett Allen form one of the best defensive combos in the league, and both of them operate well as finishers off the creation of Darius Garland and Donovan Mitchell. Fresh off signing a max extension this offseason, Mobley should continue to improve and has the potential to make a leap toward  stardom.

Quickley entered last season fresh off finishing second place in the Sixth Man of the Year vote the year before, and for the first 30 games he maintained that same role off the bench for the Knicks. At that point, he was traded to the Raptors and became their starting point guard, averaging new career bests for the final 38 games of the season: 18.6 PPG, 6.8 APG, 4.8 RPG and 2.8 3PG. As a key part of the Raptors' young nucleus, Quickley has upside to reach and surpass those levels, giving him a floor of top-60 fantasy hoops prospect and an even higher ceiling.

Johnson is expected to bring leadership and elite shooting to a rebuilding Nets squad. Last season, he averaged 13.4 PPG, 4.3 RPG, 2.4 APG, and 1.0 SPG, and hes projected to put up similar numbers this year. With his reliable scoring ability, Johnson has the chance to emerge as one of the Nets' leading scorers. As the team continues to develop, his role could expand, giving him even more opportunities to contribute both offensively and defensively.

Hartenstein parlayed a career-season with the Knicks into a new contract and starting center gig with the Thunder. Hartenstein's size, athleticism and surprisingly good passing ability from the pivot will allow Chet Holmgren to move to the power forward this season. In 49 starts for the Knicks last season, Hartenstein averaged a rounded 9 points, 9 rebounds and 3 assists with more than 2.5 combined blocks and steals while shooting 66 percent from the field and 74 percent from the line. That type of low-volume, high-efficiency double-double threat with strong defensive numbers would be enough for Hartenstein to sneak into the top-100 of both the points and category rankings entering the season.

Sochan has become one of the better defenders in the league since being drafted by the Spurs in 2022. While his offensive game is still developing, his defensive skills keep him on the court. Last season, Sochan averaged 11.6 PPG, 6.4 RPG and 3.4 APG in 29.6 MPG. Over the summer, he spent a lot of time working on improving his offensive game. If he can boost his field goal percentage, especially with Victor Wembanyama drawing attention down low, his fantasy value could rise significantly. Sochan is worth drafting late in deeper leagues.

Portis has finished third in the Sixth Man of the Year vote for two straight seasons, and is a vital cog in the Bucks' frontcourt rotation. He provides similar scoring and better rebounding than starting center Brook Lopez, but doesn't block many shots and makes just over one 3-pointer per game. In points leagues, Portis and Lopez both rank near the back of the top-100. But without Lopez's contributions to the sparser categories, in category leagues Portis ranks outside of the top-130.
